"use strict";(self.webpackChunk_N_E=self.webpackChunk_N_E||[]).push([[2897],{72897:function(e){e.exports=JSON.parse('[{"id":"q1","category":"Theory","question":"The Rate Limiting spec compares four algorithms. Why does the Fixed Window algorithm have a \'double burst\' vulnerability that the Sliding Window and Token Bucket algorithms avoid?","options":["Fixed Window uses in-memory storage that resets on server restart, losing count data","Fixed Window resets its counter at the window boundary — an attacker can send max requests at the END of one window (e.g., 11:59:59) and max requests at the START of the next (12:00:00), effectively sending 2x the allowed rate in a single second","Fixed Window counts only POST requests, allowing GET floods without restriction","Fixed Window is single-threaded and cannot handle concurrent requests accurately"],"correct":1,"explanation":"The spec documents Fixed Window (15-minute window, max 100 requests) and its vulnerability. At window boundary 12:00:00: an attacker sends 100 requests at 11:59:50 (end of old window) and 100 more at 12:00:01 (start of new window) — 200 requests in 11 seconds. Sliding Window uses a rolling ZSET in Redis tracking timestamps of each request within the last N seconds — no boundary reset. Token Bucket maintains a bucket that refills at a constant rate (10 tokens/second, max 100) — bursts are allowed up to bucket capacity but cannot double.","hint":"Think about what happens at exactly the window boundary — can an attacker exploit the counter reset to send double the allowed rate in a short burst?"},{"id":"q2","category":"Theory","question":"The Rate Limiting architecture shows three enforcement layers: Edge (CDN/WAF), API Gateway, and Application. Why enforce at all three rather than just the Application layer?","options":["Three layers are required for PCI-DSS compliance in financial applications","The Application layer is 10x faster at rejecting requests than CDN edge nodes","Defense in depth — CDN blocks volumetric floods before they consume bandwidth (Cloudflare blocks at >10K req/min); API Gateway throttles per-service abuse before it reaches application code; Application enforces per-user business rules. Each layer stops what the layer above cannot distinguish","AWS charges less when rate limiting is distributed across multiple services"],"correct":2,"explanation":"The spec documents a tiered approach: Cloudflare/WAF (volumetric DDoS, >10K req/min → CAPTCHA, >50K req/min → block 24h) → API Gateway (per-route service quotas) → Application (per-user tier limits: anonymous < free < pro < enterprise). Each layer serves a different threat model. A CDN can\'t enforce per-authenticated-user limits (it doesn\'t know user identity). The application can\'t efficiently absorb 50K req/second volumetric floods — that burns through CPU before any response. The spec also lists \'Internal services allowlisted\' to avoid false positives.","hint":"What kind of attack can a CDN block that your application code cannot handle efficiently? What can your application enforce that the CDN doesn\'t know?"},{"id":"q3","category":"Practical","question":"This rate limiter is deployed behind an AWS Application Load Balancer. What is the critical production bug?","code":"import rateLimit from \'express-rate-limit\';\\n\\nconst limiter = rateLimit({\\n  windowMs: 15 * 60 * 1000,  // 15 minutes\\n  max: 100,                   // 100 requests per window\\n  message: \'Too many requests\',\\n  keyGenerator: (req) => req.ip,  // Rate limit by IP\\n});\\n\\napp.use(\'/api/\', limiter);","codeLanguage":"typescript","options":["`windowMs` uses milliseconds but should use seconds for ALB compatibility","`req.ip` returns the ALB\'s IP address (10.0.x.x or the ALB\'s public IP), not the client\'s real IP — every user on the internet shares one rate limit bucket and gets blocked after 100 total requests. Fix: `app.set(\'trust proxy\', 1)` so Express reads the real client IP from the `X-Forwarded-For` header set by the ALB","The limiter applies to all HTTP methods — it should only restrict POST requests to prevent blocking GET-heavy pages","`max: 100` is too restrictive for a production API — production rate limits should be at least 1000 requests per window"],"correct":1,"explanation":"The spec documents: \'Trust proxy configured correctly.\' Behind a load balancer, `req.ip` returns the ALB\'s private IP or the last hop\'s IP — not the client\'s real IP. Without `trust proxy`, ALL clients share one rate limit counter and the service becomes globally inaccessible after 100 total requests. With `app.set(\'trust proxy\', 1)`, Express reads `X-Forwarded-For: 203.0.113.1, 10.0.1.4` and uses the first (leftmost) IP as `req.ip` — the actual client address. The spec also notes configuring separate Redis stores for distributed rate limiting.","hint":"In your infrastructure, what IP does `req.ip` return when the request has passed through a load balancer? Who does the ALB forward requests from?"},{"id":"q4","category":"Practical","question":"Your distributed rate limiter uses a Redis cluster. The Redis cluster experiences a 45-second complete outage. What is the safest behavior for your application during this window?","options":["Block ALL requests until Redis recovers — unavailability is safer than potential abuse","Fail open: allow all requests through during the outage, log the Redis failure and alert immediately, and use an in-memory counter as a rough guard against extreme floods — then restore Redis-based limiting automatically on recovery","Permanently ban all IPs that sent requests during the Redis outage window","Switch to a database-backed rate limiter during the Redis outage"],"correct":1,"explanation":"The spec documents the fail-open vs fail-closed tradeoff. Blocking all requests during a Redis outage means your entire API becomes unavailable because of a rate-limiter failure — a secondary system taking down the primary service. The spec\'s pattern: fail open (allow requests) + immediate alerting + fallback in-memory limiting as a rough guard. The 45-second window of open access is an acceptable tradeoff vs. complete service unavailability. After Redis recovers, the distributed limiter resumes automatically. The spec also recommends Redis Cluster (3+ nodes) to minimize single-node failures.","hint":"Should a rate limiter failure cause your entire API to go down? What\'s the impact of 45 seconds of open access vs. 45 seconds of total unavailability?"},{"id":"q5","category":"Theory","question":"According to the Rate Limiting Production Checklist, what specific request limit applies to authentication endpoints, and what does `skipSuccessfulRequests: true` accomplish?","options":["100 requests per 15 minutes; `skipSuccessfulRequests` prevents false positives for legitimate users logging in frequently","5 requests per 15 minutes per IP; `skipSuccessfulRequests: true` means only FAILED login attempts count toward the limit — successful logins don\'t deplete the allowance, specifically targeting credential-stuffing bots that test many wrong passwords","10 requests per minute; `skipSuccessfulRequests` caches valid sessions to bypass rate checks on subsequent requests","50 requests per hour; `skipSuccessfulRequests` disables rate limiting after the first successful authentication in a session"],"correct":1,"explanation":"The spec specifies auth limiter: `max: 5, skipSuccessfulRequests: true` with a 15-minute window per IP. The design insight: a legitimate user might log in once successfully — that doesn\'t deplete their 5-attempt allowance. A credential-stuffing bot trying thousands of username/password combinations generates only failed requests — each failed attempt counts down the allowance toward lockout. This asymmetry maximizes friction for attackers while maintaining a smooth experience for real users. The spec also requires account lockout after 5 failed attempts → 15-minute block.","hint":"A legitimate user logging in successfully vs. a bot trying thousands of wrong passwords — which type of request should count toward the rate limit?"}]')}}]);